1587","1620":"1620","1653":"1653","1564":"1564","1597":"1597","1596":"1596","1585":"1585","about 1620":"circa 1620","about 1564":"circa 1564","1605":"1605","South Brent, Devon, England":"South Brent, Devon, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","South Brent, Devonshire, England":"South Brent, Devon, England","Rattery, Devonshire, England":"Rattery, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Rattery, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Rattery, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1564–about 1620":"about 1564–about 1620","1568–1643":"1568–1643","1589–1653":"1589–1653","1590–1653":"1590–1653","1596–1597":"1596–1597","1599–1601":"1599–1601","1605–1668":"1605–1668","1564–1620":"1564–1620","Feb 1597":"February 1597","1571":"1571","1590":"1590","18 February 1589/90":"18 February 1590","1569":"1569","1668":"1668","1601":"1601","1568":"1568","1589":"1589","1600":"1600","1599":"1599","1643":"1643","1587":"1587","1620":"1620","1653":"1653","1564":"1564","1597":"1597","1596":"1596","1585":"1585","about 1620":"about 1620","about 1564":"about 1564","1605":"1605","South Brent, Devon, England":"South Brent, Devon, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","South Brent, Devonshire, England":"South Brent, Devon, England","Rattery, Devonshire, England":"Rattery, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Rattery, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Rattery, Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bunker","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname, of Norman origin, for a reliable or good-hearted person, from Old French <i>bon</i> ‘good’ + <i>cuer</i> ‘heart’ (from Latin <i>cor</i>).","German (<b>Bünker</b>): variant of <b>Bönker</b> (see   Boenker  ).","History: Bunker Hill in Charlestown, MA, was named as land assigned in 1634 to George Bunker of Charlestown, who had emigrated from Odell in Bedfordshire, England."],"variants":[{"name":"Banker","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>banker</i>, <i>banc(o)ur</i>, <i>bankquer</i>, <i>bankert</i> ‘covering of tapestry or other fabric for a bench, couch, or chair; ornamental hanging’, possibly a nickname or occupational name for someone who made or sold such things.","English: occupational name possibly from Middle English <i>benker</i>, seemingly ‘maker of benches’ but recorded only in names.","English: perhaps a variant of   Bunker  ."]},{"name":"Bunkers","meanings":["Americanized form of German <b>Bünker</b> (see   Bunker  ).","Possibly also an altered form of English   Bunker  .","In some cases possibly also Dutch: perhaps a variant of <b>Benkers</b>, itself a cognate of German   Benkert  . The surname <i>Bunkers</i> is very rare in the Netherlands."]},{"name":"Boenker","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt.","German (<b>Bönker</b>):","occupational name for a carpenter, a rounded form of   Benker  ."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705205,"age":5,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":7,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":21,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":23,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705210,"age":36,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705212,"age":56,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The 